The best approach for file system statics is the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it's battle-tested and already wraps every `File.*`, `Directory.*`, and `Path.*` call you need. No custom wrapper required.

### 1. Install the package

```bash
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
```

### 2. Inject `IFileSystem` instead of using statics

In your `ReportGenerator`, replace the direct `File.*` / `Directory.*` calls:

```csharp
using System.IO.Abstractions;

public class ReportGenerator(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string GenerateReport(string reportName)
    {
        var outputDir = Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("REPORT_OUTPUT_DIR") ?? "/tmp/reports";

        if (!fileSystem.Directory.Exists(outputDir))
        {
            fileSystem.Directory.CreateDirectory(outputDir);
        }

        var reportPath = fileSystem.Path.Combine(outputDir, $"{reportName}.txt");
        fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(reportPath, $"Report: {reportName}");

        return reportPath;
    }
}
```

### 3. Register in DI (Program.cs)

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```bash
dotnet add <TestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem();
mockFs.Directory.CreateDirectory("/tmp/reports");

var generator = new ReportGenerator(mockFs);
var path = generator.GenerateReport("Sales");

Assert.True(mockFs.File.Exists(path));
Assert.Contains("Sales", mockFs.File.ReadAllText(path));
```

---

> **Bonus:** I also see `DateTime.UtcNow` and `Environment.*` in `ReportGenerator.cs`. Since you're on .NET 10, `DateTime.UtcNow` can be replaced with the **built-in `TimeProvider`** (no NuGet needed), and `Environment.*` calls would need a small custom `IEnvironmentProvider` wrapper. Want me to generate those too?
